EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

With the rise of technology, one of the most affected business sectors is the Movie Industry. The Movie Industry has been always a lucrative business. With the right Marketing and Sales Strategy, every movie production will be a box office hit. Due to this, the Movie Industry has been doing a lot of reformations in its Marketing Steps and one this are the heavy use of movie trailers for each of their movie production.

Nowadays, movie trailers can be seen left and right, and especially in video sharing platforms like YouTube. Movie studios use the surge of YouTube users to freely market their movie. With the use of movie trailers, they can attract and entice viewers who were able to see the movie trailers on YouTube. With this strategy, a lot of users of YouTube will be looking forward to the movie. In This paper, we will be tackling the correlation of movie trailers on the movie success on Three Success Factors, namely: Movie Awards, Movie Ratings, and Movie Earnings.

To discuss such correlation, Top 100 Movies Titles from 2020 until 2010 was web scraped from Rotten Tomatoes website. Rotten Tomatoes is one of the leading movie critic rating platforms on the web as of present which makes it a viable source of information. Using the generated movie titles, additional information from IMDb (another leading movie database) was extracted using web scraping. Such information includes movie profits, movie rating, movie awards and nominations and the likes. Using also the Movie Title, Movie Trailer Information was extracted in YouTube Website using web scraping and YouTube API. Such Information includes view counts, likes and dislikes count and many more. Using all the extracted data, the paper was able to conclude significant findings.

Using the data, the research paper was able to conclude a significant insight. It was observed that the most important factor in a movie trailer is the view count. The Movie Trailer Views Count has a string linear relationship to Movie Success in all three success factors. This means that Greater Number of View Counts will result to success in terms of Movie Rating, Movie Awards and Movie Earnings.

INTRODUCTION

As of 2020, the movie industry has a $33 Billion US Market Size [1]. This proves that the movie Iindustry is lucrative business venture. During its growth, the movie industry has implemented different marketing strategies to produce significant gross profit through the year. With the rise of technology and internet, the movie industry is expanding its areas of marketing. As of present. With heavy usage of the internet nowadays, the movie industry has been using a lot of video sharing platforms to market and entice viewers to watch their produced movie. One of these marketing strategies is to make movie trailers out of the movies and upload to video platforms like YouTube. Movie Trailers are about 2 minute videos that contains snippets of scenes from the Movie. Movie trailers, in a sense, acts a video summary depicting a general genre and plot of the movie. Due to this, a surge of movie trailer can be seen left and right in YouTube. Can Movie trailers affect a Movie Success? Its Movie Ratings? Earnings? Awards?

Rotten Tomatoes

Rotten Tomatoes (RT) is one of the leading movies and TV series review website at present day. It was initially founded and made back in 1998. Currently Rotten Tomatoes Domains has a monthly unique visitor amounting to 26 Million globally. This means that it is heavily used by a lot of users for different purposes. RT has different movie rating features. The process is that RT first collect online reviews from certified members of various guild and films critic associations and calculates the percentage of positive reviews. To be a Certified to be a Rotten Tomatoes Critics, there are certain protocols that are needed to be addressed and passed first. Some of its unique movie rating features are the Tomatometer Ranking wherein movies are tagged as either Certified Fresh, Fresh or Rotten, depending on their rating. There is an Audience score rating where it calculates the percentage of registered users who rated the film positively on a 5–star scale[2]. Within Rotten Tomatoes, there are a lot of different groupings of ratings, and for this paper, we will be using Rotten Tomatoes Top 100 Movie Per year, from 2010 to 2020. Figure 1 Shows the top page of Top Movies Section of RT.

Figure 1. Sample Rotten Tomatoes Page

IMDB

Like Rotten Tomatoes, IMDb is one of the leading online movie rating websites. IMDb (Internet Movie Database) houses a lot of information pertaining to not only movie ratings and movie critics/reviews but also film trivia, production crew name and personal biographies. Its database has more information on the specific movie title comparing to rotten tomatoes. As of Present, IMDb Database has almost 6.5 Million Titles from movies to tv series episodes and a lot more. For this Paper, we will be cross-referencing information from the Top 100 Movies Titles from Rotten Tomatoes from IMDb Database to find additional information.[3] Figure 2 show a sample movie from IMDB.

YouTube and Movie Trailers

YouTube is an online video sharing platform owned by Google. It hosts billions of different videos by billions of different users. A lot of movie companies utilize youtube to freely extend their movie's marketing across youtube's userbase through movie trailers. These movie trailers contain snippets of the movie itself to make viewers excited for the upcoming showing. Movie trailers on the YouTube have different information like number of views, likes and dislikes. Within this paper, we would like to find the correlation of the movie trailer information on how it can bring success to the movie.

PROBLEM STATEMENT

Can Youtube movie trailer statistics be indicative of Movie success in terms of earnings, ratings and awards?¶

BUSINESS VALUE
  • Cinemas: These correlations can be used for forecasting demand based on official trailer performance. Cinemas can optimize the scheduling of the movies to maximize profit.
  • Producers: Forecast revenues based on its trailer performance
  • Marketing: Give insights on how to best market movies

OVERVIEW OF THE METHODOLOGY¶

Each step will be discussed in detail in the following sections. To give a general overview of the methodology, a brief description for each step is described below:

1. Data Gathering¶

  • Rotten Tomatoes webscraping: Website scraping of the top 100 movies per year listed for the last 10 years (2020 to 2010) from the top Movie Rating.

  • IMDB API and webscraping: Movie titles retrieved from rotten tomatoes were then used to obtain complementary information from IMDB. The OMDB API was used to gather relevant information. The imdb ids from the API were then used to retrieve more movie information and was done via webscraping.

  • Youtube API Using the scraped Movie Names, data on its respective official movie trailers, uploaded on YouTube were gathered via the YouTube API.

  • The data gathered for each website is stored separately in an sql database.

2. Data Preprocessing:¶

  • The gathered data was cleaned and formatted prior analysis. The steps involved are:
    • Removing duplicates
    • Converting movie titles to lower case
    • Converting numbers represented as strings to integer/float
    • Standardizing the format/naming convention for the 3 database.

The three database were then merged for analysis. and engineered variables are introduced.

3. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

  • The processed data was analyzed by obtaining basic statiscal measures, and finding the correlation of the Scraped Movie Informations and the Youtube VIdeo Trailer Informations.

4. Interpretation of Results¶

  • Analyzed the findings on EDA.
DATA GATHERING

Rotten Tomatoes Webscraping:¶

In Rotten Tomatoes, there is a section where they list all the top 100 Movies for that year according to the ratings that is stored on their website. They have a ton list ranging from different years. For limitations of research, we will be looking only the year from 2010 to 2020.

The Website scraping process is started from the initial page of Top 100 Movies of the Year 2020, characterized by the link: https://www.rottentomatoes.com/top/bestofrt/?year=2020

  1. First We will be making a simple SQL Database file and make a connection to it for us to store the information.

  2. The Program below will use the library import request to get the html code string text and then will be parsed by the beautiful soup library function. A Simple Iteration from the Year 2020 to 2010 and just changing the Year string on the link: https://www.rottentomatoes.com/top/bestofrt/?year=. We can get all the URL list for the home page listing of the top 100 Movies. Which will be then used for latter processing.

for a in toplink:
    wp = bs4.BeautifulSoup(requests.get(a, proxies=proxies).text)
    file = json.loads(wp.find_all('script')[1].string)
    x2 = 0
    list1 = []
    for x in file['itemListElement']:
        list1.append(x['url'])

    year = int(file['mainEntityOfPage'].replace('Top 100 Movies of ', ''))

    for x1 in list1:
        try:
            wp1 = bs4.BeautifulSoup(requests.get(x1, proxies=proxies).text)

            list2 = []
            list2.append(year)
            x2 = x2 + 1
            list2.append(x2)
            list2.append(wp1.title.text.replace(' - Rotten Tomatoes', ''))

            z = ''
            for x in wp1.find_all(name='div', class_="mop-ratings-wrap__half"):
                z1 = (x.text.strip().replace('\n', '').replace(
                    '  ', '').replace('\xa0', ' '))
                z = z+z1+'&&&'

            list2.append(''.join(re.findall(r'(.*?)TOMATOMETER', z)))
            list2.append(''.join(re.findall(r'Total Count: (.+?)&&&', z)))
            list2.append(''.join(re.findall(r'&&&(.+?)Audience', z)))
            list2.append(''.join(re.findall(r'Ratings: (.+?)&&&', z)))

            y = ''
            for x in wp1.find_all(name='li', class_="meta-row clearfix"):
                y1 = (x.text.strip().replace('\n', '').replace(
                    '  ', '').replace('\xa0', ' '))
                y = y+y1+'&&&'

            list2.append(''.join(re.findall(r'Rating:(.+?)&&&', y)))
            list2.append(''.join(re.findall(r'Genre:(.+?)&&&', y)))
            list2.append(''.join(re.findall(r'Directed By:(.+?)&&&', y)))
            list2.append(''.join(re.findall(r'Written By:(.+?)&&&', y)))
            list2.append(''.join(re.findall(r'In Theaters:(.+?)&&&', y)))
            list2.append(''.join(re.findall(r'On Disc/Streaming:(.+?)&&&', y)))
            list2.append(''.join(re.findall(r'Box Office:(.+?)&&&', y)))
            list2.append(''.join(re.findall(r'Runtime:(.+?)&&&', y)))
            list2.append(''.join(re.findall(r'Studio:(.+?)&&&', y)))

            with conn:
                conn.execute(
                    """INSERT INTO mytable VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, 
                    ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?,?, ?)""", list2)

            time.sleep(2)

        except:
            print(list2)

To extract movie information from IMDB, the OMDB api, which is a RESTful web service was used. Sending data requests in OMDB api, requires an api key. The api key is then inserted into the url: http://www.omdbapi.com/?apikey={api_key}&t='where &t= is followed by the query, which in this case, is the movie title.

The movie titles from rotten tomatoes stored in dataframe were the iterated and for each iteration, the movie title is inserted to the url and HTTP requests were done using the python requests library. This returns a movie's information, such as 'Title', 'Year', 'Rated', 'Released', 'Runtime', 'Genre', 'Director', 'Writer', 'Actors', 'Plot', 'Language', 'Country', 'Awards', 'Poster', 'Ratings', 'Metascore', 'imdbRating', 'imdbVotes', 'imdbID' in json format. Each returned information is appended to a list as shown below:

IMDB also records information about the the financial performance of a movie such as gross sales, opening weekend sales and movie budget. However, this information is not included when using the API. The financial data was therefore obtained using webscraping. The html code was obtained using the requests library. As illustrated in Figure 6, the movie's financial information is under div.h4 with class = inline, and the numbers needed are siblings to the text. Beautiful soup library was used to pull out this information from the html code. The implementation is as shown below:

In [ ]:
# Scraping financial information such as movie budget and sales

financial_info = pd.DataFrame(columns=['imdb ID', 'Budget',
                                       'Open Weekend USA',
                                       'Gross USA', 'WW Gross'])
for i, j in enumerate(imdb_id):
    try:
        finance = []
        re = requests.get(f'https://www.imdb.com/title/{j}/', proxies=proxies)
        a = bs4.BeautifulSoup(re.text)

        if a.find_all('h4', class_='inline', text=['Budget:']):
            finance.append(a.find_all('h4', class_='inline', text=[
                           'Budget:'])[0].next_sibling.strip())
        else:
            finance.append(np.NaN)

        if a.find_all('h4', class_='inline', text=['Opening Weekend USA:']):
            finance.append(a.find_all('h4', class_='inline', text=[
                           'Opening Weekend USA:'])[0].next_sibling.strip())
        else:
            finance.append(np.NaN)

        if a.find_all('h4', class_='inline', text=['Gross USA:']):
            finance.append(
                a.find_all('h4', class_='inline',
                           text=['Gross USA:'])[0].next_sibling.strip())
        else:
            finance.append(np.NaN)

        if a.find_all('h4', class_='inline',
                      text=['Cumulative Worldwide Gross:']):
            finance.append(
                a.find_all('h4', class_='inline',
                           text=['Cumulative '
                                 'Worldwide Gross:'])[0].next_sibling.strip())
        else:
            finance.append(np.NaN)

        financial_info.loc[i] = [j] + finance
        time.sleep(1)
    except:
        pass

The information stored in imdb_1 is converted to a dataframe, and merged with the financial info and converted to an sqlite3 database.

imdb_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Title','imdb ID','Rated','Released','Awards',
                                'imdbRating','imdbVotes','MetaCritic',
                                'Country','Plot','Genre'])

for index,item in enumerate(imdb_1):
    try:
        title = item['Title']
        imdbID = item['imdbID']
        rated = item['Rated']
        released = item['Released']
        award = item['Awards']
        imdbrating = item['imdbRating']
        votes = item['imdbVotes']
        metascore = item['Metascore']
        country = item['Country']
        plot = item['Plot']
        genre = item['Genre']
        
    except KeyError as e:
        item[e] = np.nan
    except:
        pass
        
    imdb_df.loc[index] = [title,imdbID,rated,released,award,imdbrating,votes,
                          metascore,country,plot,genre]

# Drop duplicates
imdb_df = imdb_df.drop_duplicates(subset='imdb ID', keep="first")

# Merge imdb dataframe and financial info based on imdb ID
imdb_final = pd.merge(imdb_df,financial_info, on='imdb ID', how='left')

#Save to imdb database
con_db = sqlite3.connect('imdb_dataset.db')
imdb_final.to_sql('imdb',con_db)

Web Scraping to find the corresponding URL of the Official Trailer on Youtube¶

Using a simple program, we can use the movie title from rotten tomatoes, attach an "Official Trailer" string to the title, and attach this to the search query link of website which is https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query= . Forming this URL, we can now use a request get function to gets it html code. This html code actually have the list of the top most official trailer for the corresponding movie title. We can get the top most offical trailer and get its youtube id which will be used for the youtube api.

Upon having the youtube id, we can use the youtube api to query the needed informations. For this youtube api, we only use the https://www.googleapis.com/youtube/v3/videos since youtube api has a limited quota. Using the youtube id collected, we can use it to get the statistics and content details. From this statistics we can get the likes, dislikes and etc.

The informations collected will be appended to a list which will be then transferred to a database file. The program below shows this.

DATA DESCRIPTION

Overall the Research Paper was able to generate 3 Database Files which corresponds to each Website, namely: Rotten Tomatoes Database, IMDB Database, YouTube Database, Each of this Database has 1100 Rows of Data representing the Top 100 Movies of each year from 2020 to 2010 (Based on Rotten Tomatoes). Each of the Database has different numbers of Columns. The succeeding table/cells will describe the Data Contents of each Database:

Rotten Tomatoes Database

Column Name Description
Year Year when it was considered at the Top 100
Position Position in the Top 100
Title Name of the Movie
Tomatometer Score Percentage of positive Critic reviews
Total Count Number of Total Count of Verified Critic Review
Audience Score Percentage of registered users who have rated the film positively on a 5-star scale
Verified Ratings Number of Verified Audience Ratings
Rating Movie Viewer Rating allowed
Genre Specific Genre of the Movie
Directed by Name of the Director of the Movie
Written by Name of Writer for the Movie
In_Theaters Date of Showing in Movie Theaters
On Disc Streaming Date of Showing on Disc
Box Office Amount of the Movie achieved when in Box Office
Run Time Total Length of the Movie
Studio Name of Studio who created the Film/Movie

DATA PREPROCESSING

Data extracted will be cleaned prior analysis. First of, as observed there are cells with null values. These rows won't be dropped since there are other important data on those rows.

Rotten Tomatoes Dataframe processing¶

For Faster Processing,let's pull all of these integer type columns to one specific dataframe. Some needed processing of specific columns are as follows:

1. Tomatometer_Score = Take out the Percentage Sign
2. Audience_Score = Take out the Percentage Sign
3. Runtime = Take out the minute word
4. Box_Office = Take out the Dollar Sign
5. Duration Trailer = Show in Minutes

Year, Tomatometer Score, Total Count,Audience Score, Verified_Ratings, Box_Office, Runtime are converted to a numeric data type. Movie titles are converted to lower case and the movie year appending to the movie is removed.

In [6]:
import pandas as pd
pd.options.mode.chained_assignment = None
df_rt = df_rt[['Year', 'Position', 'Title', 'Tomatometer_Score', 'Total_Count',
               'Audience_Score', 'Verfied_Ratings', 'Box_Office', 'Runtime']]
df_rt['Year'] = pd.to_numeric(df_rt['Year'])
df_rt['Position'] = pd.to_numeric(df_rt['Position'])
df_rt['Tomatometer_Score'] = pd.to_numeric(
    df_rt['Tomatometer_Score'].str.replace('%', ""))
df_rt['Total_Count'] = pd.to_numeric(df_rt['Total_Count'].str.replace(',', ''))
df_rt['Audience_Score'] = pd.to_numeric(
    df_rt['Audience_Score'].str.replace('%', ""), errors='coerce')
df_rt['Verfied_Ratings'] = pd.to_numeric(
    df_rt['Verfied_Ratings'].str.replace(',', ''), errors='coerce')
df_rt['Box_Office'] = df_rt['Box_Office'].str.replace(',', '').replace('$', '')
df_rt['Box_Office'] = pd.to_numeric(df_rt['Box_Office'].str.replace('$', ''))
df_rt['Runtime'] = pd.to_numeric(df_rt['Runtime'].str.replace('minutes', ''))
df_rt['Title'] = df_rt.Title.str.lower().str.extract('(.+) \(\d{4}\)?')
df_rt = df_rt.set_index('Title', drop=True)

rot_index = [(re.sub(r'\([^()]*\)', '', index)).lower().strip()
             for index in df_rt.index]
df_rt.index = rot_index

IMDB Dataframe processing¶

Numeric variables such as imdb ratings, votes, budget, gross sales, opening weekend sales are converted to a numeric data type. Awards column, which initially combines all awards and nominations into a single string was split and a column for major and minor awards won and nominations was created. Movie titles are converted to lower case and the movie year appending to the movie is removed.

df_imdb['Major_Awards_Win'] = df_imdb.Awards.str.extract('[wW]on (\d+)')

                                'Released', 'Country', 'Plot'])

        r',', '').apply(pd.to_numeric, errors='coerce')

Youtube DataFframe Processing¶

Youtube: Column: View_Count, Like_Count, Dislike_Count, Comment_Count are converted to a numeric data type. Duration trailer is formatted as PTXMYS, where X and Y are the number of minutes and seconds, respectively. The X and Y information was extracted and formatted in terms of number of minutes. Movie titles were then converted to lower case, and year appended to it removed.

In [8]:
df_yt = df_yt[['Movie', 'View_Count', 'Like_Count',

yt1 = yt1.replace(np.nan, 0, regex=True)
yt1 = yt1.astype(int)

yt2 = yt2.replace(np.nan, 0, regex=True)
yt2 = (yt2.astype(int))/60
yt3 = yt1 + yt2

df_yt['Duration_Trailer'] = yt3
df_yt.Movie = df_yt.Movie.str.lower()
df_yt = df_yt.set_index('Movie', drop=True)

            for index in df_yt.index]

INSIGHTS/EDA

To determine if a movie's official trailer and movie's success has some correlation or relationship, Exploratory Data Analysis was performed. It should be noted that in this study, a movie's success is defined in three ways: Movie ratings (from imdb and rotten tomatoes), Movie Earnings (Gross Sales, Profit) and Movie Awards (Major / Minor awards won).

First, we need to narrow down the dataframes to only include relevant columns. Additionally, we have to convert some columns into numerical values to make it easier to perform operations with.

Let's introduce some engineered variables.

  • Like_Ratio = Like_Count / (Dislike_Count + 1); +1 to prevent undefined values
  • Like:View_Ratio = Like_Count / View_Count)
  • Profit = World Wide Gross Sales - Budget
In [12]:
df_score['Like_Ratio'] = df_score.Like_Count / (df_score.Dislike_Count + 1)
df_score['Like:View_Ratio'] = df_score.Like_Count / (df_score.View_Count)
df_score['Profit'] = df_score['WW Gross'] - df_score['Budget']

print('% of movies with recorded Worldwide Gross Sales: ', 
      df_score['WW Gross'].dropna().size/df_score.shape[0])

Since this study is primarily about finding correlation with trailers and movie success.Observations will be limited to youtube statistics and movie success defined above.

These are the observations from figure 9:

Youtube statistics and movie ratings correlation:

  • Number of views, likes, dislikes, comments has no correlation with rotten tomato ratings.
  • Numbers of views has a slight positive correlation with imdb rating.
  • The like:dislike and like:view ratio shows little to no correlation with success. Since the number of likes and dislikes scale proportional to views, the number of likes and dislikes themselves are not insightful.
  • Number of views, likes, dislikes, comments has a weak correlation with audience score.

Youtube statistics and movie earnings correlation:

  • Number of views,likes,dislikes,comments, has a strong positive correlation with Gross sales, opening weekend sales, profit.
  • The like:dislike shows no correlation while like:view ratio shows a slight correlation.

Youtube statistics and movie awards correlation:

  • Number of views has a slight positive correlation with major awards win and slightly stronger correlation with Minor awards win and nominations.
  • The number of like,dislike,comments and like:dislike and like:view ratio has no correlation with major awards.
  • The number of dislikes has a slight positive correlation with respect to minor awards while number of likes does not.

The number views and movie earnings was shown to have the highest correlation among the three indicators of success. Let's plot the variables together to see if any obvious trends can be seen:

RESULTS AND DISCUSSION

Movie success can be difficult to quantify as a single number. Instead, it can be much easier to interpret movie success as a result of three factors: Awards, Ratings and Earnings.

Youtube movie trailer statistics were somewhat related but nowhere near comprehensive indicators of movie success. Each factor of success had varying correlations and indicators from trailers. Let's explore the insights we found for each factor.

Ratings Success:¶

As a preface, it should be mentioned that the number of likes and dislikes are proportional to the number of views, and are not immediately representative of the "likeness" of the trailer. Instead, we look at the *proportion* of like:views and like:dislike to gauge the actual likeness of a trailer.

From the EDA section, it was observed that no correlation was seen between rotten tomatoes score and trailer statistics such as number of views, likes, dislikes and comments. Imdb on the other hand shows a slight positive correlation with the number of views. The lack of correlation in rotten tomatoes can perhaps be due to the more stringent requirements rotten tomatoes have in rating movies. This can be interpreted also to be the independence of critic rating (RT score) of the public reception (Youtube stats).

Also, by segregating the higher rated movies in imdb and rotten tomatoes based on the 50th percentile,it was shown that higher rated movies in IMDB tend to have a higher number of views with a 122% difference between higher / lower rated movies. Like:dislike ratio is also quite higher for higher rated movies with a 42.18% difference. The opposite was observed for rotten tomatoes. Higher rated movies have 181.95% lower number of views. No differece was seen for like:dislike ratio though. Again, this is likely attributed to RT's higher standards and criterieas that goes beyond popularity.

Earnings Success¶

It was observed that profit and the total number of views for trailer had a strong positive linear relationship, with a pearson correlation coefficient 0.72.

There was a slight correlation between like:view ratio and profit and no correlation with like:dislike ratio. This suggests that earnings are more dependent on views rather than likeness. Furthermore, upon closer inspection with a scatter plot, it was shown that movie with a like:view ratio greater than 0.0135 generally managed to earn more than the median, except for one outlier.

Awards and Nominations¶

From the EDA section, no correlation was seen between the number of awards a movie has with the view count or the likeness of the movie. But by segregating movies with at least 1 major award versus movies with 0 awards, movies with awards have a number of views, on average, 739% higher than movies without. It was also observed that movies with major awards have a 7.6% higher like:dislike ratio.

The difference is slightly pronounced in minor awards, but is significant, nonetheless. Movies with minor awards have a 129% higher number of views. Unlike major awards, movies with or without minor awards have no significant differences in terms of like:dislike ratio (0.8%).

CONCLUSION AND RECOMMENDATION

A list from Rotten Tomatoes' top 100 movies from 2010 to 2020 were referenced to IMDB and Youtube data which were obtained via webscraping and API requests. Results show that trailer view counts can be somewhat indicative of movie success. Movie success was defined as a composition of three factors: Awards, Earnings and Ratings. Each factor had its own correlation and indicators to movie trailer statistics. Comprehensively, though, youtube trailer statistics aren't very powerful indicators of movie success.

From the EDA, the strongest indicator in all three factors of success was trailer view count. IMDb and Audience rating were gauged to be higher with higher views. Similarly, Profit and number of views had a strong linear relationship. Lastly, movies with at least one 1 major award had 739% more views on average.

This study was limited to the top 100 movies per year from the year 2010 to 2020. It is recommended to increase the scope of the data to have a better understanding of the relationship between movie success and official movie trailers. In addition, these study can be further expanded into a machine learning problem by trying to predict if a movie can be a box office success based on trailer performance.
